Saturdays, 2:30-5:30pm with Resident Teacher, Gen Kelsang Tonglam

The Foundation Program (FP) is open to anyone who would like an opportunity to deepen their understanding and experience of Buddhism through systematic weekly teachings and guided meditations.

In-depth study on the book, Universal Compassion, a commentary to Geshe Chekhawa’s Training the Mind in Seven Points by Venerable Geshe Kelsang Gyatso Rinpoche. This book is about transforming even the most difficult daily life experiences into opportunities for spiritual growth through developing and enhancing minds of universal love and compassion.

The Main Benefits of Foundation Program are:
• Deeper understanding of the meditations
• Structure to help establish a regular meditation practice
• More support for your spiritual growth
• An opportunity to discuss and ask questions
• Gain the ability to integrate Buddha’s teachings into our daily lives and solve all our human problems

The Teacher
Gen Kelsang Tonglam is the National Spiritual Director for East Asia of the New Kadampa Tradition – International Kadampa Buddhist Union and Resident Teacher of Kadampa Meditation Centre Taiwan. Gen Tonglam has studied and practised Kadampa Buddhism for over twenty years under the guidance of his Spiritual Guide, Venerable Geshe Kelsang Gyatso Rinpoche. He is renowned for his ability to present Buddha’s most profound teachings in simple and most practical ways, injecting a renewed enthusiasm and driving force in our ordinary life.

description:
1st Annual Boomer Babe Sunday "Swishing Party!"   Think Free Shopping!

Swishing is the easy way to update your wardrobe! It’s guilt free shopping with no cost to your wallet. Swishing works like a giant clothes swap: you bring items you no longer wear and exchange them for something new-to-you!

What to do with all those beautiful clothes, shoes, and accessories that are still good, but just don't fit your new style, size, or closet? They don't make the wardrobe cut, but too good to just 'give away to strangers?’  Or maybe you have well-intended gifts to get rid of.

The Boomer Babe solution?  Our 1st annual Babe SWISHING GALA! 

Here’s the deal. We each bring 5 nice, clean, presentable clothes, accessories, jewelry and other wonderful items that are lurking unloved in our wardrobe, and other Babes fall in love with them and give them a good home.

You might bring one sweater and take two pairs of shoes, or hang a party frock on the ‘Swishing Rail’ and take a pair of skinny jeans and feather boa...

Here are the Rules of the Swish:

-  Everyone brings at least 5 items of quality clothing and something delicious to share and eat. You set out your clothes and then browse other offerings, while balancing your plate of yummy goodies and glass of wine.

-  No item may be claimed before the swish opens. 

-  We go around and share info/detail on one specific 1 item we hold dear and are donating.

-   Once everyone had a chance to go around, the free trading begins!

~  No spitting, no scratching and no fighting!

We all enjoy an afternoon potluck and libations and go home with our 'new' items. The identity of our SECRET BABE HOSTESS will be revealed when we send details to get you to her beautiful home!

RSVP only if you mean it!
name: 1st Annual Boomer Babe Sunday "Swishing Party!" Sun, 9/17, 1:00 p.m. Think FREE!

description:
We can launch in Ballard. There is usually a good amount of street parking close to the boat ramp, but on my last visit, no bathrooms were in sight. (A Trader Joe's market is nearby).
From the boat ramp, we can head under the Ballard Bridge to Salmon Bay, and explore the Ballard Locks. (But we won't go through the locks, not today.) Then, we can head the other direction down the ship canal to the Fremont Bridge, and maybe as far as Gasworks Park, before turning around to return to the ramp. Depending on what we decide along the way, this could be about a 5 to 7 mile paddle.
The weather report for Thursday looks dry and sunny, with light winds, although temps are still below mid-60s. Maybe it will be even better as the day approaches, so let's remain flexible. As always, let me know if something else works better for you, like a later start time or a different day.
And finally, using meetup costs $180 per year, but I never want to charge for a membership fee, nor charge a fee to participate. I do want to thank everyone who has asked to share that cost by donating some cash when they see me. I appreciate your support.

Buddha’s Day and Multicultural Festival, now in its 22nd year, is a major annual attraction held in Federation Square which commemorates the Buddha’s Birthday and celebrates the City of Melbourne’s multicultural and multi-faith society.

The event showcases traditional Buddhist ceremonies such as Bathing the Buddha, Tea Meditation, Twilight Light Offering Ceremony as well as multicultural music and dance performances, social and spiritual well-being lectures, world peace prayers, tai chi classes, interfaith ceremony, children’s activities, animal farm and more.

The much anticipated ‘Taste of Asia’ Vegetarian Food Fair will spread the length of the River Terrace offering vegetarian delights for all to enjoy.


Just in case anyone is wondering about the Law and Taking photographs in a public place, here is some information on photographers rights

 https://www.artslaw.com.au/images/uploads/Street_photographers_rights_2016.pdf

Enjoy us for a fun, at times naughty, Rag Bag Cabaret Spring Fling and Edinburgh Fundraiser on the May long weekend. The show will feature professional comedy, music, burlesque and circus acts -- a little rag bag of everything! 

Belinda was blown away by the hilarity and entertainment in February 2017 at Rag Bag's Valentine's Cabaret on Roncy. The Spring Fling is expected to be even better!!! Producer Luke Jackson says: "The Spring Fling is something of a "Rag Bag Classic" with all of our very favourite performers from the last six years. It’s going to be brilliant. Plus it’s raising money for our run at the Edinburgh Fringe Festival!"

Our group will save almost 35 per cent off the regular price. Our tickets will be just $20. Members must purchase their ticket(s) in advance to get this discount!

• Mindreading magic man Lukas Stark

description:
We can launch in Ballard. There is usually a good amount of street parking close to the boat ramp, but on my last visit, no bathrooms were in sight. (A Trader Joe's market is nearby). 

 
From the boat ramp, we can head under the Ballard Bridge to Salmon Bay, and explore the Ballard Locks. (But we won't go through the locks, not today.) Then, we can head the other direction down the ship canal to the Fremont Bridge, and maybe as far as Gasworks Park, before turning around to return to the ramp. Depending on what we decide along the way, this could be about a 5 to 7 mile paddle. 

The scenery will be highly urban and industrial.  Salmon Bay is the home of the fishing fleet.  The ship canal is almost like a city street on the water, with people and buildings visible on both sides.  When the salmon are running (not now, I don't think), you can actually see them jumping out of the water all over the place near the locks.  Of course, the locks are interesting to see from a kayak perspective.  

 
The weather report for Thursday looks dry and sunny, with light winds, although temps are still below mid-60s. Maybe it will be even better as the day approaches, so let's remain flexible. As always, let me know if something else works better for you, like a later start time or a different day. 

 
And finally, using meetup costs $180 per year, but I never want to charge for a membership fee, nor charge a fee to participate. I do want to thank everyone who has asked to share that cost by donating some cash when they see me. I appreciate your support.
name: Paddle Salmon Bay and the Ship Canal

The event showcases traditional Buddhist ceremonies such as Bathing the Buddha, Tea Meditation, Twilight Light Offering Ceremony as well as multicultural music and dance performances, social and spiritual well-being lectures, world peace prayers, tai chi classes, interfaith ceremony, children’s activities, animal farm and more.

The much anticipated ‘Taste of Asia’ Vegetarian Food Fair will spread the length of the River Terrace offering vegetarian delights for all to enjoy.


Just in case anyone is wondering about the Law and Taking photographs in a public place, here is some information on photographers rights

Meet at Fed Square information centre 11am

There is a Buddha's Day Purification Ceremony with the giant Buddah at 11am to 12pm so we will look at this first and then wander around soaking up the colour and activity of this mulitcultrual festival in honour of Buddha.
